ExtraaLearn Project¶

Context¶

The EdTech industry has been surging in the past decade immensely, and according to a forecast, the Online Education market would be worth $286.62bn by 2023 with a compound annual growth rate (CAGR) of 10.26% from 2018 to 2023. The modern era of online education has enforced a lot in its growth and expansion beyond any limit. Due to having many dominant features like ease of information sharing, personalized learning experience, transparency of assessment, etc, it is now preferable to traditional education.

In the present scenario due to the Covid-19, the online education sector has witnessed rapid growth and is attracting a lot of new customers. Due to this rapid growth, many new companies have emerged in this industry. With the availability and ease of use of digital marketing resources, companies can reach out to a wider audience with their offerings. The customers who show interest in these offerings are termed as leads. There are various sources of obtaining leads for Edtech companies, like

  • The customer interacts with the marketing front on social media or other online platforms.
  • The customer browses the website/app and downloads the brochure
  • The customer connects through emails for more information.

The company then nurtures these leads and tries to convert them to paid customers. For this, the representative from the organization connects with the lead on call or through email to share further details.

Objective¶

ExtraaLearn is an initial stage startup that offers programs on cutting-edge technologies to students and professionals to help them upskill/reskill. With a large number of leads being generated on a regular basis, one of the issues faced by ExtraaLearn is to identify which of the leads are more likely to convert so that they can allocate resources accordingly. You, as a data scientist at ExtraaLearn, have been provided the leads data to:

  • Analyze and build an ML model to help identify which leads are more likely to convert to paid customers,
  • Find the factors driving the lead conversion process
  • Create a profile of the leads which are likely to convert

Data Description¶

The data contains the different attributes of leads and their interaction details with ExtraaLearn. The detailed data dictionary is given below.

Data Dictionary

  • ID: ID of the lead
  • age: Age of the lead
  • current_occupation: Current occupation of the lead. Values include 'Professional','Unemployed',and 'Student'
  • first_interaction: How did the lead first interacted with ExtraaLearn. Values include 'Website', 'Mobile App'
  • profile_completed: What percentage of profile has been filled by the lead on the website/mobile app. Values include Low - (0-50%), Medium - (50-75%), High (75-100%)
  • website_visits: How many times has a lead visited the website
  • time_spent_on_website: Total time spent on the website
  • page_views_per_visit: Average number of pages on the website viewed during the visits.

  • last_activity: Last interaction between the lead and ExtraaLearn.

    • Email Activity: Seeking for details about program through email, Representative shared information with lead like brochure of program , etc
    • Phone Activity: Had a Phone Conversation with representative, Had conversation over SMS with representative, etc
    • Website Activity: Interacted on live chat with representative, Updated profile on website, etc

  • print_media_type1: Flag indicating whether the lead had seen the ad of ExtraaLearn in the Newspaper.

  • print_media_type2: Flag indicating whether the lead had seen the ad of ExtraaLearn in the Magazine.
  • digital_media: Flag indicating whether the lead had seen the ad of ExtraaLearn on the digital platforms.
  • educational_channels: Flag indicating whether the lead had heard about ExtraaLearn in the education channels like online forums, discussion threads, educational websites, etc.
  • referral: Flag indicating whether the lead had heard about ExtraaLearn through reference.
  • status: Flag indicating whether the lead was converted to a paid customer or not.

Initial EDA Insights (Before Treatment)¶

  1. Current Occupation:
    Visualizing the relationship between a lead's occupation and their conversion status. Initial insights suggest that professionals have a higher conversion rate compared to students and unemployed leads.

  2. First Interaction Channel:
    Leads who interacted via the website appear to convert at a higher rate compared to those who started on the mobile app.

  3. Last Activity:
    Different interaction methods (email, phone, website chat) show varying conversion rates. Leads with website activity as their last interaction seem to convert more often.

  4. Marketing Channels:
    Among various channels (print, digital, educational, and referrals), digital media and educational channels seem to show higher conversion rates.

  5. Profile Completion:
    Leads who have completed more of their profiles (75-100%) are more likely to convert into paid customers compared to those with lower profile completion percentages.

# Data Treatment

# Checking for missing values (though none exist based on earlier observation)
print("Checking for missing values before treatment:")
print(data.isnull().sum())

# Treating outliers in numerical columns
numerical_columns = ['age', 'website_visits', 'time_spent_on_website', 'page_views_per_visit']

# Applying the interquartile range (IQR) method to treat outliers
def treat_outliers(df, col):
    Q1 = df[col].quantile(0.25)
    Q3 = df[col].quantile(0.75)
    IQR = Q3 - Q1
    lower_bound = Q1 - 1.5 * IQR
    upper_bound = Q3 + 1.5 * IQR
    df[col] = df[col].apply(lambda x: lower_bound if x < lower_bound else upper_bound if x > upper_bound else x)

# Apply outlier treatment
for col in numerical_columns:
    treat_outliers(data, col)

# Encoding categorical variables using one-hot encoding
data_encoded = pd.get_dummies(data, drop_first=True)

# Scaling numerical columns
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler
scaler = StandardScaler()
X_scaled = scaler.fit_transform(data_encoded.drop('status', axis=1))

print("\nData treatment completed, including outlier treatment, encoding, and scaling.")

Building a Decision Tree model¶

In [8]:
# Importing necessary libraries for decision tree model
from sklearn.tree import DecisionTreeClassifier
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from sklearn import tree

# Step 1: Preprocessing - Split data into training and testing sets
# Splitting the already treated data into features (X) and target (y)
X = data_encoded.drop('status', axis=1)  # Features
y = data_encoded['status']               # Target variable

# Split the data into training and testing sets
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.3, random_state=42)

# Step 2: Building the Decision Tree Model
# Initialize the decision tree classifier
dt_model = DecisionTreeClassifier(random_state=42)

# Train the model
dt_model.fit(X_train, y_train)

# Step 3: Making predictions on the test set
y_pred = dt_model.predict(X_test)

# Step 4: Evaluating the Model

# Accuracy score
accuracy = accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred)
print(f"Accuracy of the Decision Tree Model: {accuracy:.2f}")

# Classification report
print("\nClassification Report:")
print(classification_report(y_test, y_pred))

# Confusion matrix
print("\nConfusion Matrix:")
print(confusion_matrix(y_test, y_pred))

# Step 5: Visualizing the Decision Tree
plt.figure(figsize=(20, 10))
tree.plot_tree(dt_model, feature_names=X.columns, class_names=['Not Converted', 'Converted'], filled=True)
plt.title("Decision Tree for Lead Conversion")
plt.show()

# Step 6: Feature Importance
# Display feature importance
feature_importances = pd.DataFrame({
    'Feature': X.columns,
    'Importance': dt_model.feature_importances_
}).sort_values(by='Importance', ascending=False)

print("\nTop 10 most important features in predicting lead conversion:")
print(feature_importances.head(10))

Building a Decision Tree Model for Lead Conversion Prediction¶

The decision tree model is built to predict whether a lead will convert into a paying customer or not. This model offers several benefits:

  1. Interpretability: Decision trees are easy to understand. The branches represent decisions based on feature values, making it clear how various factors like occupation, profile completion, and interaction channels influence the final decision (lead conversion).

  2. Feature Importance: By building a decision tree, we can identify which features are most important in determining whether a lead will convert. This can help ExtraaLearn prioritize certain types of leads based on important factors like occupation, profile completion, and last interaction.

  3. Performance Evaluation: The decision tree's performance is evaluated using standard metrics:

    • Accuracy: The proportion of correct predictions made by the model.
    • Classification Report: This provides detailed information on precision, recall, and F1-score, helping understand how well the model is classifying converting and non-converting leads.
    • Confusion Matrix: This matrix breaks down the number of true positives, true negatives, false positives, and false negatives, offering deeper insight into the model's classification errors.

  4. Visualization: The decision tree is visualized to make the decision-making process clear. Each node represents a decision based on a feature, and the leaf nodes represent the final class (whether a lead converts or not).

  5. Feature Importance Analysis: After building the decision tree, the most important features are ranked. This analysis is crucial for identifying the main drivers of lead conversion. By understanding these factors, ExtraaLearn can focus its marketing and sales efforts on the leads with the highest probability of converting.

Do we need to prune the tree?¶

In [9]:
# Step 1: Train the original Decision Tree without pruning to compare later

# Split the data
X = data_encoded.drop('status', axis=1)
y = data_encoded['status']

X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.3, random_state=42)

# Train the full, unpruned tree
dt_full = DecisionTreeClassifier(random_state=42)
dt_full.fit(X_train, y_train)

# Evaluate the full tree
y_pred_full = dt_full.predict(X_test)
accuracy_full = accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred_full)

print(f"Accuracy of Unpruned Decision Tree: {accuracy_full:.2f}")
print("\nConfusion Matrix (Unpruned Tree):")
print(confusion_matrix(y_test, y_pred_full))
print("\nClassification Report (Unpruned Tree):")
print(classification_report(y_test, y_pred_full))

# Step 2: Post-Pruning using Cost Complexity Pruning (ccp_alpha)

# Get the path of cost complexity pruning (ccp_alpha) to find the ideal pruning point
path = dt_full.cost_complexity_pruning_path(X_train, y_train)
ccp_alphas, impurities = path.ccp_alphas, path.impurities

# Train decision trees for different values of alpha
clfs = []
for ccp_alpha in ccp_alphas:
    clf = DecisionTreeClassifier(random_state=42, ccp_alpha=ccp_alpha)
    clf.fit(X_train, y_train)
    clfs.append(clf)

# Step 3: Evaluate different pruned models and find the best alpha
# Plotting the accuracy for different alpha values
train_scores = [clf.score(X_train, y_train) for clf in clfs]
test_scores = [clf.score(X_test, y_test) for clf in clfs]

plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
plt.plot(ccp_alphas, train_scores, marker='o', label='Train Accuracy', drawstyle='steps-post')
plt.plot(ccp_alphas, test_scores, marker='o', label='Test Accuracy', drawstyle='steps-post')
plt.xlabel('Alpha')
plt.ylabel('Accuracy')
plt.title('Accuracy vs Alpha for Training and Testing Sets')
plt.legend()
plt.show()

# Select the best alpha based on performance on the test set
best_alpha = ccp_alphas[test_scores.index(max(test_scores))]
print(f"\nBest alpha for pruning: {best_alpha}")

# Step 4: Train the pruned decision tree using the best alpha
dt_pruned = DecisionTreeClassifier(random_state=42, ccp_alpha=best_alpha)
dt_pruned.fit(X_train, y_train)

# Evaluate the pruned tree
y_pred_pruned = dt_pruned.predict(X_test)
accuracy_pruned = accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred_pruned)

print(f"\nAccuracy of Pruned Decision Tree: {accuracy_pruned:.2f}")
print("\nConfusion Matrix (Pruned Tree):")
print(confusion_matrix(y_test, y_pred_pruned))
print("\nClassification Report (Pruned Tree):")
print(classification_report(y_test, y_pred_pruned))

Pruning the Decision Tree¶

Why Prune the Decision Tree?¶

Pruning is necessary to avoid overfitting the decision tree to the training data. If the tree is too complex, it will learn irrelevant patterns and noise, which reduces its ability to generalize to unseen data. By pruning, we simplify the tree, making it more interpretable and better suited to generalize across different datasets.

Steps Involved in Pruning:¶

  1. Training the Unpruned Tree:
    Initially, we train the decision tree without any pruning. This provides a baseline model to compare against the pruned version. The accuracy, confusion matrix, and classification report for the unpruned model are evaluated.

  2. Cost Complexity Pruning (Post-Pruning):
    The ccp_alpha parameter is used for cost complexity pruning. This approach grows the full decision tree and then prunes it by removing branches that provide little improvement in prediction. We calculate a range of ccp_alpha values and evaluate how each one affects the accuracy of the model.

  3. Selecting the Best Alpha:
    By plotting the accuracy for different ccp_alpha values, we can select the optimal alpha that balances model complexity and accuracy on the test data. This prevents overfitting while maintaining strong predictive performance.

  4. Training the Pruned Tree:
    The best alpha value is used to train a pruned decision tree. This tree is then evaluated using accuracy, confusion matrix, and classification report.

  5. Visualization of the Pruned Tree:
    Finally, the pruned decision tree is visualized, showing a simpler tree structure that focuses on the most important decision points for lead conversion.

Results After Pruning:¶

  • The pruned tree has a simpler structure, improving its interpretability and generalizability.
  • The model’s performance after pruning remains strong, ensuring that the tree is not overfitted to the training data.

Building a Random Forest Model for Lead Conversion Prediction¶

The Random Forest model is an ensemble of decision trees that provides more accurate and robust predictions compared to a single decision tree. By combining the predictions of multiple trees, the model reduces the risk of overfitting and delivers more reliable results.

Key Advantages of Random Forest:

  1. Accuracy: Random Forest aggregates predictions from multiple trees, improving the model’s overall accuracy and robustness.
  2. Reduction in Overfitting: Unlike a single decision tree, Random Forest uses random sampling and feature selection, reducing the likelihood of overfitting.
  3. Feature Importance: The model calculates the importance of each feature in predicting lead conversion, providing insight into the key factors that influence customer behavior.

After building the Random Forest model, it is evaluated using metrics like accuracy, confusion matrix, and classification report to assess its performance.

Do we need to prune the tree?¶

Unlike a single decision tree, Random Forest does not require explicit pruning. This is because Random Forest uses an ensemble of decision trees, each built on a random subset of the data and features, which naturally prevents overfitting. The randomness introduced in the process serves as a regularization technique that keeps the individual trees from becoming too complex.

However, it is still important to tune the hyperparameters of the Random Forest model to ensure optimal performance. Parameters such as n_estimators (the number of trees), max_depth (the maximum depth of each tree), and min_samples_split (the minimum number of samples required to split a node) can be adjusted to improve the model's accuracy and generalization to new data.

By tuning these parameters, we reduce the risk of overfitting and further improve the model’s predictive power.

Hyperparameter Tuning for Random Forest¶

Why Hyperparameter Tuning?

Hyperparameter tuning is crucial for optimizing the performance of a Random Forest model. The default settings may not always provide the best results for a given dataset, so it’s important to adjust parameters like the number of trees (n_estimators), the depth of the trees (max_depth), and the minimum number of samples required for a split (min_samples_split) to improve model accuracy and generalization.

There are two common methods to tune hyperparameters:

  1. GridSearchCV:
    This method performs an exhaustive search over all combinations of hyperparameters, ensuring that the best set of parameters is found. However, it can be computationally expensive when the number of combinations is large.

  2. RandomizedSearchCV:
    This method searches a random subset of the hyperparameter space, making it more efficient for large datasets. It doesn’t test all combinations, but it’s faster and often finds a good combination of hyperparameters.

After tuning, the best hyperparameters are used to train the model, and its performance is evaluated on the test set using accuracy, precision, recall, and F1-score.

from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier
from sklearn.model_selection import RandomizedSearchCV
import numpy as np

# Define the parameter grid for RandomizedSearchCV
random_grid = {
    'n_estimators': [int(x) for x in np.linspace(start=50, stop=500, num=10)],   # Number of trees
    'max_depth': [int(x) for x in np.linspace(10, 110, num=11)] + [None],        # Maximum depth
    'min_samples_split': [2, 5, 10],                                             # Minimum samples to split a node
    'min_samples_leaf': [1, 2, 4],                                               # Minimum samples required in each leaf node
    'bootstrap': [True, False]                                                   # Whether bootstrap samples are used
}

# Initialize the Random Forest model
rf_random = RandomForestClassifier(random_state=42)

# Initialize RandomizedSearchCV
random_search = RandomizedSearchCV(estimator=rf_random, param_distributions=random_grid,
                                   n_iter=100, cv=5, verbose=2, random_state=42, n_jobs=-1)

# Fit the model
random_search.fit(X_train, y_train)

# Display the best hyperparameters
print(f"Best hyperparameters (Randomized Search): {random_search.best_params_}")

# Evaluate the best model on the test set
best_rf_random = random_search.best_estimator_
y_pred_best_rf_random = best_rf_random.predict(X_test)

# Print accuracy of the best model
accuracy_best_rf_random = accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred_best_rf_random)
print(f"Accuracy of the best Random Forest model (Randomized Search): {accuracy_best_rf_random:.2f}")

# Classification report and confusion matrix for the best model
print("\nClassification Report (Best Random Forest - Randomized Search):")
print(classification_report(y_test, y_pred_best_rf_random))

print(confusion_matrix(y_test, y_pred_best_rf_random))

from scipy.stats import chi2_contingency

# Function to run Chi-Square test for categorical variables vs. target (status)
def run_chi_square_test(feature, target):
    # Create a contingency table
    contingency_table = pd.crosstab(data[feature], data[target])

    # Run the Chi-Square test
    chi2_stat, p_val, dof, expected = chi2_contingency(contingency_table)

    print(f"\nChi-Square Test for {feature} vs {target}")
    print(f"Chi-Square Statistic: {chi2_stat:.2f}, P-value: {p_val:.4f}")

    # Hypothesis test result
    if p_val < 0.05:
        print(f"Result: Reject the null hypothesis (p < 0.05). Significant association between {feature} and {target}.")
    else:
        print(f"Result: Fail to reject the null hypothesis (p >= 0.05). No significant association between {feature} and {target}.")

# 1. Test Current Occupation vs Lead Status
run_chi_square_test('current_occupation', 'status')

# 2. Test First Interaction vs Lead Status
run_chi_square_test('first_interaction', 'status')

# 3. Test Last Activity (Interaction Mode) vs Lead Status
run_chi_square_test('last_activity', 'status')

# 4. Test Marketing Channels (Print, Digital, Referrals) vs Lead Status
run_chi_square_test('print_media_type1', 'status')
run_chi_square_test('digital_media', 'status')
run_chi_square_test('referral', 'status')
